```

The output I expect to see is:

```
Something { test: [Getter: 'test'] }
```

Feature request:
So currently i'm working with an application where I need to send the address of a node Buffer to a  ioctl() to communicate with a linux device driver correctly. 

Currently every Buffer allocated gets an address reference, example in a 32-bit architecture : 
```javascript
var myBuf = Buffer.alloc(1);
console.log(myBuf); // prints Buffer where 0x210c378 may be the memory address
// Result:  
// <Buffer 00>
```

The idea is to provide a function that returns the address of the Buffer (e.g. **Buffer.address**) example:
```javascript
var myBuf = Buffer.alloc(1);
console.log(myBuf);
console.log(myBuf.address); // should include all left zeros
// Result:
// <Buffer 00>
// 0210c378
```

Therefore if I want to make a structure that in C/C++ looks like this
```C
struct myStruct {
  char *tx;
  int value;
}
```

Then in node I can create the structure like this
```javascript
var tx = Buffer.from([1, 2, 3, 4]);                // char tx[4], an example
var pointerToTx = Buffer.from(tx.address,'hex');   // char *tx
var value = Buffer.alloc(4);                       // int value
var myStruct = Buffer.concat([pointerToTx, value]) // struct myStruct {char *tx, int value}
console.log(myStruct);  // prints pointer address and a int value buffer
// Result: 
// <Buffer 02 10 c3 78 00 00 00 00> 
```

The current way of getting the address is using napi/nan modules. I believe at some point there was an implementation in node for getting the memory address of Buffers but not sure. If there is already an implementation for this then please let me know.

