My proposal is to extend React with a small hook that allows us to mutate nodes without causing render:

```jsx
import React, { useMutation }

function A() {
  const [specialRef, set] = useMutation()

  useEffect(() => {
    // the following would execute sync and without causing render
    // going through the same channel as a regular props update with all
    // the internal interpolation (100 --> "100px")
    set({ style: { left: 100 } })
  }, [])

  return <div ref={specialRef} ... />
```

This would make the react eco system essentially cross platform in one strike. It uses the fact that reconcilers know how to handle props, something we don't know in userland unless we cause render to set fresh props, which is not at all optimal for animation or anything frame based. react-dom for instance knows what `margin: 3px` is, react-three-fiber knows what `position: [1,2,3]` is, and so on. These details are defined in the reconciler:

```jsx
  commitUpdate(instance: any, updatePayload: any, type: string, oldProps: any, newProps: any, fiber: Reconciler.Fiber)
```

If libraries could use this knowledge from outside they could deal with any platform. Animation libraries like react-spring or framer-motion could animate everything: dom nodes, react native views, meshes, hardware diodes. We could finally write libraries that are not reliant on platforms.

