Offered spherical deformation for noobs. The syntax is simple:

``` javascript
Object.Dent( origin, direction, radius, depth ) ;
```

`origin`\- point where the applied strain
`direction` - deformation direction ( usually the opposite of normal )
`radius` - deformation radius 
`depth` - deformation depth, 0<depth<1

Maybe there is a better name than Dent. erichlofs used a THREE.Ray.intersectSphere. 

So, for example, will look like deformation of objects with the mouse:

``` javascript
if ( intersects.length > 0 ) 
    {
        var face = intersects[ 0 ].face;
        var direction = new THREE.Vector3(); direction.copy( face.normal );
               // direction.multiplyScalar( -1 ); 
        var obj = intersects[ 0 ].object; 
        obj.Dent( intersects[ 0 ].point, direction, 80, 0.5 ) ;
    }
```

Example: <a href = "http://neftek.legko.ufanet.ru/MyWebGL/three.js/examples/DentModifier.html"> here </a>

Code:

``` javascript
THREE.Mesh.prototype.Dent = function ( origin, direction, radius, depth ) 
    {
        var M = new THREE.Matrix4().getInverse( this.matrixWorld );
        var origin = origin.applyMatrix4( M ) ;

        var normal = new THREE.Vector3(); normal.copy( direction );
        normal.multiplyScalar( -radius*( 1-depth ) ); 

        var centerSphere = new THREE.Vector3(); centerSphere.addVectors( origin, normal );  
        var Sphere = new THREE.Sphere( centerSphere, radius );

    for (var i=0; i< this.geometry.vertices.length; i++)
        {       
            if ( centerSphere.distanceTo( this.geometry.vertices[i] ) < radius )
                {
                    var Ray = new THREE.Ray( this.geometry.vertices[i], direction );
                    var punct = Ray.intersectSphere( Sphere );          
                    this.geometry.vertices[i] = punct;
                }           
        }

    this.geometry.computeFaceNormals();
    this.geometry.computeVertexNormals();
    this.geometry.verticesNeedUpdate = true;
    this.geometry.normalsNeedUpdate = true; 
    }
```

