If a user registers an event handler w/ a EventDispatcher instance and then tries to remove a handler for another event type, three.js will throw an error. This is demonstrated with the following example:

``` javascript
var foo = new THREE.EventDispatcher();
var handler = function(){};
foo.addEventListener('eventA', handler);
foo.removeEventListener('eventB', handler);
```

Resulting in:

```
TypeError: listeners[type] is undefined
var index = listeners[ type ].indexOf( listener );
```

Technically this is a user error, but the following patch takes care of this case in the same manner that EventDispatcher#removeEventListener uses checks to see if this._listeners is defined, and if not simply returns:

```
--- a/three-r62.js
+++ b/three-r62.js
@@ -6716,7 +6716,7 @@ THREE.EventDispatcher.prototype = {

        removeEventListener: function ( type, listener ) {

-               if ( this._listeners === undefined ) return;
+               if ( this._listeners === undefined || this._listeners[type] === undefined) return;
```

Putting this out there for inclusion and/or just to help others who encounter the same issue.

